snippet.textDisplay:
I had the pleasure of driving a 1992 Silhouette with the 3800 engine in High School and College. Some fun/unusual facts that were missed:
1. All reasonably priced cars in the 90's sucked, in 1992 the silhouette with the 3800 engine as actually the most powerful minivan out there, in high school I would regularly out accelerate my friends with "normal" cars like accords and civics.
2. They came with a built in air compressor in the drivers side rear hatch side, it was insanely powerful and useful. The van needed it because at least the version I had, had rear air bag suspension for heavy loads. If you removed the two rear seats and folded the middle three forward you could fit five 1/2 kegs of beer in the rear of the van. At this point the compressor was running continuously the whole ride home to fill the air bags.
3. The best trick of all: Use the windshield squirters and shoot washer fluid all over the front windshield, then quickly turn the massive wipers on the fastest setting. In this manner you could shoot washer fluid a clear 15-20 ft to side of the car soaking innocent bystanders.

snippet.textDisplay: I have to defend these little vans. They were great on mpg getting as much as 30mpg. It wasn't unusual to see them with over 200k miles on them.  As for the bad, The 3.1, 3100 and 3400 hundreds were known for intake gasket leaks and blowing head gaskets if pushed hard. With the introduction of the 3800 put in them the only problems were some had to have the crank sensor replaced. The 3800 v6 in the past was known as a 231 V6 which was used in the Buick Grand National turbo charged. With options like Super Charging or Turbo Charging you could get big HP numbers out of the 3800V6.

snippet.textDisplay:
The problem with the child seat was that it's a child seat. Children grow. In Canada you have to use one until they're 8. Babies and children grow. In Canada, all child seats have an expiration date. If labels or instructions become faded, they're also considered no good and supposed to be thrown out. So, while it may have been cool at the time, nowadays it is a waste. Especially if they were trying to keep one model for all of NA. Of course it's not hard to have different seats for different countries, but trying to follow the rules of all the states and countries you ship to ends up being a nuisance. It also hurts the value of the vehicle if a country changes law mid life cycle. ie: a year after it comes out.

For that reason, the child seat is a failure, not a feature.
-Recall hundreds, hundreds of thousands of seats, because Canada(or anywhere changes laws).
Edit: You could, in the past, get a child seat safetied, for a fee. However, if you got into any accident, regardless of how/what, a child safety seat is supposed to be decommissioned.
Also, you're not supposed to sell or give away the seat, as it's hard to keep track of it's history. Just so much crazy red tape to go through.
So, they likely had to by law, destroy those seats if they ever reached a landfill/scrapyard.
My eldest sister curled her nose when I mentioned this van, as her and her husband had looked at this and considered buying it in the past, but didn't BECAUSE of the childseat built in.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm still using 1993 Pontiac Trans Sport 3.8 litre daily. It's really great car. In Europe Pontiac had the same body as this Oldsmobile version. You didn't say anything about built-in compressor for automatic level controll of back suspension or just inflating broken tire ;) The rear seats were in 1990s one of the lightest and that's why it was quite easy to get them out of the car. It weighted just only 15 kg. I don't know if yours 3.4 litre is broken or what (the smoke behind) but 3.8 litre version is quite nice sprinter and its acceleration is quite good in my opinion, especially as for minivan. You can do 100 km/h (62.14 mph) in about 9-10 sec. - even nowadays it's nice time for average sedan/hatchback in Europe. Its fuel consumption is also nice (considering the engine capacity) because you can achieve around 15 litres/100 km in european-city driving, what is about 2-3 litres less than Chrysler Voyager 3.8 or Ford Windstar 3.8 from the same years.
